Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
2:50 PM; Case called for Hearing.  Prosecuting attorney Zachary A Wittchow in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Ambernae S Lane in court. Court confirms with the defendant that the address in the file is current.  Court inquires if the defendant plans to retain counsel.  Defendant advises that she was not eligible for a Public Defender but cannot afford private counsel.  Court inquires if the defendant is aware of the offer.  State recites the offer on the record. Defendant presents statements.  Based on the defendant's statements court believes her circumstances may have changed.  Court recommends the defendant contact the PD's office again.  Court takes a break at 2:54 p.m. to allow time for the defendant to call the PD's office and if she does not qualify fill out a court appointed petition.
Court reconvenes at 3:08 p.m.  Same appearances.
Court will approve the petition for appointment of counsel.
Defendant is to pay $50.00 per month commencing 9-15-2022.
Hearing scheduled for September 12, 2022 at 10:00 am.
Effective August 1, 2022, this case is assigned to Branch 7 Judicial Vacancy, pursuant to 22-SO-04(67).
Returned Summons filed by the State. (Return to Sender, Vacant, Unable to forward).

Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed.  Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Defendant is not to possess any dangerous weapons/firearms (the Defendant can use/possess a firearm only if the Defendant is enrolled in a certified CCW class).
